    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 24, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Google gave the inbox a night shift\n\nThe personal agent pitch has reached its obvious destination: your email, your calendar, and a small cloud worker that never clocks out.\n\n- **The launch:** Google introduced Gemini Spark at I/O as a 24/7 personal AI agent built from Gemini models and Antigravity agent tooling.\n- **The machinery:** Sundar Pichai said Spark runs on dedicated Google Cloud virtual machines, so long tasks can continue after the laptop shuts.\n- **The lock-in:** Google also bundled the I/O wave into Search, Gemini, Android, Firebase and AI Studio, because platform gravity remains the least subtle model capability.\n\n*The assistant is no longer in your browser. It has a lease in your workflow.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/19/google-introduces-gemini-spark-a-24-7-agentic-assistant-with-gmail-integration/) | [Google](https://blog.google/innovation-and-ai/technology/ai/google-io-2026-all-our-announcements/)\n\n---\n\n## 🌊 Waymo discovered weather is not a test fixture\n\nRobotaxis are excellent until the road turns into soup and the fallback plan is a press statement.\n\n- **The pause:** Waymo halted service in Atlanta, San Antonio, Dallas and Houston after robotaxis struggled with heavy rain and flooded roads.\n- **The incident:** TechCrunch says an empty Waymo vehicle drove into a flooded Atlanta street and stayed stuck for about an hour before recovery.\n- **The regulator:** NHTSA told TechCrunch it is aware and in contact with Waymo, while the company still lacks a final remedy after last week's flood-related software recall.\n\n*Autonomy continues to meet the ancient adversary: standing water.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/21/waymo-pauses-service-in-four-cities-as-robotaxis-keep-driving-into-floods/)\n\n---\n\n## 🎙️ The cockpit recorder got resurrected badly\n\nAI has found another boundary case nobody wanted: turning accident evidence into posthumous content.\n\n- **The removal:** The NTSB temporarily pulled public access to its docket system after people reconstructed voices from a UPS Flight 2976 cockpit spectrogram.\n- **The loophole:** Federal law bars cockpit audio from public dockets, but the accident file included a spectrogram image that encoded enough signal for reconstruction attempts.\n- **The cleanup:** The agency restored docket access Friday but kept 42 investigations closed for review, including the Louisville crash file.\n\n*The public record remains public. The dead pilots did not volunteer for synthetic audio demos.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/22/ai-is-being-used-to-resurrect-the-voices-of-dead-pilots/) | [NTSB](https://x.com/NTSB_Newsroom)\n\n---\n\n## 🧾 Altman turned tokens into seed checks\n\nOpenAI found a way to make startup credits feel like venture capital, which is efficient if you own the meter.\n\n- **The offer:** Sam Altman offered $2 million in OpenAI tokens to every startup in the current Y Combinator batch.\n- **The cohort:** YC has about 169 companies in the class, and TechCrunch says the deal would be structured as an uncapped SAFE converting at the next priced round.\n- **The catch:** OpenAI gets equity exposure and nudges young companies toward its stack before Anthropic, Google or anyone else becomes the default habit.\n\n*Free compute is never just free compute. Sometimes it is cap table architecture.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/20/sam-altman-makes-mic-drop-offer-to-every-y-combinator-startup/) | [Sam Altman](https://twitter.com/sama/status/1925217195626008903)"
  }
]
